Prelude
"Please!" Queen Elvin pleaded, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with royal advisors standing by. The queen had given birth to a girl. Just thinking about it made the Ice King frown.
The infant girl looked just like her mother: pale blue eyes, snow-white hair, with a few strands of blue hair dotted in. The Ice King thought having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he had only sons.
"You have two choices, either kill this child or leave her out in the wilderness. Elvin, this is your punishment." He said her name bitterly, as if it were poison. He always did.
The Kingdom of Frost was not always a single kingdom. It used to be divided into two parts, northern and southern. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom filled with magical powers. Because of the north's greed, the two kingdoms waged endless wars until the south proposed a truce.
At that time, the southern kingdom had already fallen into despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to stop this bloody conflict. They proposed that their only princess be married to the north, becoming the queen of the north, and give birth to a son who would be the future king. Afterwards, the south would merge with the north to establish a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Elvin thus married Prince Akur.
"Please, my king, for the safety of my child, you can do anything to me—imprison me, exile me, or even kill me." Queen Elvin pleaded, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen, filled with hatred. Perhaps, just perhaps, he would have a shred of pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him when he was at his lowest, and had given him children.
"Fine. The child can live in the palace." Hearing the Ice King's words, the queen sighed in relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Elvin both showed expressions of terror. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you command, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisors to take the queen's daughter to an empty room belonging to Elvin. After that, he commanded the soldiers to take Elvin to the execution ground where all the citizens could see.
As the soldiers escorted her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen—also the kindest queen—about to be executed, and they felt very angry. Some cried, some shouted and tried to attack the soldiers, and some wanted to know why this was happening; but they all had the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Elvin approached the wooden post, the most terrifying person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner for the burning. The former queen Elvin would be burned alive. No one should be executed by fire, even criminals. In the Kingdom of Frost, fire execution was the cruelest punishment.
Elvin was tied to the wooden post, and the king began to speak about how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Kingdom of Frost refused to believe it and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden post, and a single tear rolled down the former queen's face.
"Carly, live on!" With these words, Queen Elvin's life came to an end.
Silence filled the hall.
In the southern wing of this cold palace, an endless "tapping" sound came from the room on the far left. The servants who passed by always wondered what was inside the room, yet they were too afraid to get close. The maids walked around the hall, whispering among themselves, spreading various rumors. Some believed that the late queen Elvin of the Ice King was living in this room, waiting to be set free.
They were very wrong. Avery thought, as he walked toward the southern wing. The servants walked back and forth by the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside at all.
Of course, there were also many rumors about TA, because TA was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Avery whispered to this complex door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, symbols of the royal family.
TA didn't know if she would actually let him in this time, which was different from before. I still have bruises from last time. Avery recalled this and couldn't help but laugh. At that time, Carly threw a book at him, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A light sound came from inside the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere, just staying there.
"May I come in?" Avery asked, TA couldn't forget the consequences of entering without being invited last time.
A light sound came again from the room. It seemed to be saying, "Come in." Avery felt a chill, not sure if it was from the cold or the voice. Although TA had been there for many years, Avery still felt a bit strange hearing the sound from inside the room.
"I'm coming in," Avery said, slowly opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but it was expected. Papers were everywhere in the room. Books were scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures in the room. There were no windows, and there was almost no light. It was also colder than other parts of the palace (which indicated many problems). The room looked as if it had been hit by a blizzard, with everything in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, covered with blankets, reading a notebook. A small lantern lit up the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Avery asked, sitting beside Carly's bed.
